{'push_id': 9360957128, 'size': 215, 'distinct_size': 9, 'ref': 'refs/heads/kroikie-rc-emulator', 'head': 'e63d8c79fc1de5d474c4c0ffbab599a649edea08', 'before': 'c248fa766d391ab83045b781f4281d3a013053bf', 'commits': [{'sha': 'a182bdf4346b5b3dd00e8a6e1f93a7bf8cf00d8c', 'author': {'email': 'inlined@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Thomas Bouldin'}, 'message': 'Improve functions deploy time by polling more frequently. (#3866)

* Improve functions deploy time by polling more frequently.

Our pollers are built on Throttler Queues. These have a built in
backoff rate and GCF takes so long that we will invariably backoff
until we hit the maximum. When unspecified the maximum is 1m.

Looking at a single function deploy, we can say that we previously
wasted on average 30s sleeping (assume our second to last poll was
half way through the 0-60s range). With a new limit we should waste
only 5s polling, for an average savings of 25s. The savings will
be more dramatic for deploys of multiple functions.

* sleep 10s, not 10ms', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/firebase/firebase-tools/commits/a182bdf4346b5b3dd00e8a6e1f93a7bf8cf00d8c'}, {'sha': '1771d4daacc8069fb3c039963b28cdb38896216a', 'author': {'email': 'inlined@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Thomas Bouldin'}, 'message': 'Improve image deletion. (#3865)

* Improve image deletion.

1. Delete images via the aritfactregistry API instead of the docker API.
   This fixes the issue where vestigial "packages" were left around even
   with no contained images. This also meant we didn't always delete
   caches.
2. Extend cleanupBuildImages to take a list of deleted functions so we
   can now delete those functions' images as well as their caches.
3. Added deleted-function cleanup to functions:delete
4. Fixed some stupid code styles I had where I invoked an inlined lambda
   rather than just using an expression.

Manually tested in addition to unit tests.

Functions SDK now includes a debug mode that can be enabled via environment variables to operate in ways that's useful during development. See https://github.com/firebase/firebase-functions/pull/983 for an example.

We will turn on Debug Mode and enable `skipTokenVerification` feature on the Functions Emulator. {'push_id': 9268264428, 'size': 11, 'distinct_size': 11, 'ref': 'refs/heads/kroikie-rc-emulator', 'head': 'c248fa766d391ab83045b781f4281d3a013053bf', 'before': '64daf145e6cf20620cc5a718f8cc9f5750eb7afe', 'commits': [{'sha': '5368b58f0f3199e5275f48530ea0fb77286a975e', 'author': {'email': 'inlined@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Thomas Bouldin'}, 'message': 'Improve functions deploy time by polling more frequently. (#3866)

* Improve functions deploy time by polling more frequently.

Our pollers are built on Throttler Queues. These have a built in
backoff rate and GCF takes so long that we will invariably backoff
until we hit the maximum. When unspecified the maximum is 1m.

Looking at a single function deploy, we can say that we previously
wasted on average 30s sleeping (assume our second to last poll was
half way through the 0-60s range). With a new limit we should waste
only 5s polling, for an average savings of 25s. The savings will
be more dramatic for deploys of multiple functions.

* sleep 10s, not 10ms', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/firebase/firebase-tools/commits/5368b58f0f3199e5275f48530ea0fb77286a975e'}, {'sha': 'c4bbc3bbbb704e224b1a33c4a601fcce08e6daa0', 'author': {'email': 'inlined@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Thomas Bouldin'}, 'message': 'Improve image deletion. (#3865)

* Improve image deletion.

1. Delete images via the aritfactregistry API instead of the docker API.
   This fixes the issue where vestigial "packages" were left around even
   with no contained images. This also meant we didn't always delete
   caches.
2. Extend cleanupBuildImages to take a list of deleted functions so we
   can now delete those functions' images as well as their caches.
3. Added deleted-function cleanup to functions:delete
4. Fixed some stupid code styles I had where I invoked an inlined lambda
   rather than just using an expression.

Manually tested in addition to unit tests.
